I, too, have rated this before, but I found an easier way. I put the shrimp (peeled, with tails left on) in a gallon-sized zip-lock baggie with the dry ingredients (rub) overnight or do it in the morning before work, and then complete the recipe when it's time to eat. As always, it's great! Especially if you make your own Cajun spice -- you control the heat and salt. One thing I found works: when making creole spice, substitute some of the cayenne with hot Hungarian paprika. It isn't as fiery, but it is more complex, somehow. Good stuff.

